<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-493-228  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 493 228.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  August 7 1989 n1236* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Symbolics' graphics arm puts animation and paint up on Mac withIvory CPU. (Symbolics Inc. Graphics Div.)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Symbolics Inc. Symbolics Graphics Div. (product development)Apple Computer Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    AAPL; SMBX.andO;Topic:     Computer GraphicsAnimationGraphics SoftwareMarketing StrategyWorkstations.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>SYMBOLICS' GRAPHICS ARM PUTS ANIMATION AND PAINTandM;UP ON MAC WITH IVORY CPUandM;The Chatsworth, California-based Graphics Division of SymbolicsandM;Inc, Burlington, Massachusetts has implemented its full Animation and PaintSystem for the Apple Computer Inc MacIvory systems, which add the company'sIvory co-processor to the Macintosh personal computer.andP;  The Animation andPaint System was hitherto available only on the company's 3600 family ofartificial intelligence workstations.andP;  The move, says Symbolics, is the firststep in a strategy designed to satisfy emerging demands for affordable andcomplex two- and three-dimensional graphics on industry-standard computers.andO;Graphics Division chief Tom McMahon comments that &quot;Animators and filmpost-production houses have been our primary market in the past,&quot; noting that&quot;With our Macintosh-based product we can now address the needs of a muchbroader industrial and corporate market requiring both computing power andlow cost solutions on popular workstations&quot;.andP;  Symbolics says it will thismonth also release a high performance system that it claims will reduce thecost and time to render photo-realistic images, adding that the new renderingsystem will be available on a &quot;widely-installed graphics workstation&quot;.andO;</TEXT></DOC>